  "viewBox": { "width": 760, "height": 540 },

  "theory": "A compiler is a program translator that converts source code written in a high-level programming language into target machine code. This process is divided into multiple sequential phases. (1) Lexical Analyzer (Lexer): Converts source characters into a stream of tokens. (2) Syntax Analyzer (Parser): Groups tokens into grammatical structures (Parse Tree/Syntax Tree). (3) Semantic Analyzer: Checks for type compatibility and semantic constraints. (4) Intermediate Code Generator: Produces machine-independent low-level code (e.g. three-address code). (5) Code Optimizer: Improves intermediate code speed and resource utilization. (6) Code Generator: Translates optimized code into target assembly or machine language. Throughout compilation, the Symbol Table tracks variable declarations, and the Error Handler reports syntax or type violations.",
  
  "keyPoints": [
    "6 phases: Lexical → Syntax → Semantic → IR Generation → Optimization → Code Generation",
    "Front End (Analysis): Phases 1-3 deal with source language; Back End (Synthesis): Phases 4-6 deal with target machine",
    "Symbol Table stores identifier info (name, type, scope, address) and is accessed by all phases",
    "Intermediate Code (Three-Address Code) makes compiler machine-independent and retargetable",
    "Lexical errors: illegal characters; Syntax errors: grammar violations; Semantic errors: type mismatches"
  ],

  "examTip": "6 phases: Lexical Analysis → Syntax Analysis → Semantic Analysis → Intermediate Code Gen → Code Optimization → Code Generation. First 3 = Front End (analysis). Last 3 = Back End (synthesis). Symbol Table and Error Handler span all phases.",

  "useCases": [
    "GCC, Clang, LLVM — production compilers for C, C++, Rust using all 6 phases",
    "JVM — Java compiler produces bytecode (IR) which JIT compiles to machine code at runtime",
    "Database query compilers — SQL is parsed, semantically analyzed, optimized, and executed"
  ],

